            <div type="translation">
                <p>The following of the Athenians died in Potidaea. Me, immortal, [they made
                    (?)....], to mark the virtue[....], and their ancestors[...], having died, they
                    received the monument as a victory. Ether received the souls and this very earth
                    received the bodies, and they were released around the gates of Potidaea. Some
                    of their enemies have a portion in the grave, but others, fleeing, placed the
                    wall as the surest hope for their life. This city and the people of Erectheus
                    long for [these] men, who previously died on the front lines of Potidaea, the
                    sons of the Athenians; but having placed their lives as counterweights, they
                    received virtue by fate and brought glory to the fatherland.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The original inscription from 200 BCE was discovered in Orchomenos in Boetia and
                    now is housed in the British Museum in London.</p>
